docs.abstract: Fumio Kishida, a former foreign minister, prevailed in a closely fought election to lead Japan’s governing Liberal Democratic Party.
docs.snippet: Fumio Kishida, a former foreign minister, prevailed in a closely fought election to lead Japan’s governing Liberal Democratic Party.
docs.lead_paragraph: TOKYO — In a triumph of elite power brokers over public sentiment, Japan’s governing party on Wednesday elected Fumio Kishida, a former foreign minister, as its choice for the next prime minister.

headline.main: The choice for Japan’s prime minister is a party stalwart who lagged in opinion polls.

docs.abstract: The conservatives who have been the dominant force in modern German politics suffered their worst defeat, while the Social Democrats and Greens made gains.
docs.snippet: The conservatives who have been the dominant force in modern German politics suffered their worst defeat, while the Social Democrats and Greens made gains.
docs.lead_paragraph: Germany’s mainstream conservatives, long the dominant force in the country’s politics, suffered the worst defeat in their history in the election on Sunday, faring significantly worse in every part of the country than they did in the previous election, in 2017.

headline.main: Maps show where Merkel’s party lost ground: everywhere.

docs.abstract: The two lawmakers, both from the Green Party, reflect the growing visibility and acceptance of transgender people, who have never before held seats in the Parliament.
docs.snippet: The two lawmakers, both from the Green Party, reflect the growing visibility and acceptance of transgender people, who have never before held seats in the Parliament.
docs.lead_paragraph: The name “Tessa Ganserer” did not appear on the ballot in Sunday’s election, but Ms. Ganserer still won a seat representing a district of Nuremberg, making history as one of the first two openly transgender people to join the German Parliament.

headline.main: Two transgender women win seats in the next German Parliament.

docs.abstract: The Social Democrats made significant gains on Sunday’s election but will need to find coalition partners to form a government.
docs.snippet: The Social Democrats made significant gains on Sunday’s election but will need to find coalition partners to form a government.
docs.lead_paragraph: A tired-looking Olaf Scholz took to the stage Monday morning at his Social Democratic headquarters, making clear that he saw his party’s significant gains in the election as a mandate from voters to head up the next government with the two smaller parties that also made gains in Sunday’s vote.

headline.main: Vowing to modernize industry and ‘halt man-made climate change,’ Olaf Scholz claims a mandate.

docs.lead_paragraph: Canada may be known for its cold weather, but this summer, parts of the country were an inferno.

headline.main: Climate change was supposed to be a big issue this election. It wasn’t.

docs.abstract: Voters denied him the expanded bloc of power he had been seeking in Parliament, unofficial results showed.
docs.snippet: Voters denied him the expanded bloc of power he had been seeking in Parliament, unofficial results showed.
docs.lead_paragraph: OTTAWA — Prime Minister Justin Trudeau’s political gamble failed to pay off Monday when Canadian voters returned him to office but denied him the expanded bloc of power he had been seeking in Parliament.

headline.main: Trudeau Projected to Remain Prime Minister, but Falls Short of a Majority
headline.print_headline: Snap Election in Canada Tests Trudeau’s Gamble to Hand Liberal Party a Majority

docs.abstract: Led by Senator Ron Johnson, G.O.P. officials want to eliminate a bipartisan elections agency — and maybe send its members to jail.

docs.lead_paragraph: Republicans in Wisconsin are engaged in an all-out assault on the state’s election system, building off their attempts to challenge the results of the 2020 presidential race by pressing to give themselves full control over voting in the state.

docs.abstract: With his poll numbers falling, President Jair Bolsonaro is already questioning the legitimacy of next year’s election. He has help from the United States.
docs.snippet: With his poll numbers falling, President Jair Bolsonaro is already questioning the legitimacy of next year’s election. He has help from the United States.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRASÍLIA — The conference hall was packed, with a crowd of more than 1,000 cheering attacks on the press, the liberals and the politically correct. There was Donald Trump Jr. warning that the Chinese could meddle in the election, a Tennessee congressman who voted against certifying the 2020 vote, and the president complaining about voter fraud.

headline.main: The Bolsonaro-Trump Connection Threatening Brazil’s Elections
headline.print_headline: Trump Allies Export Election Playbook to Brazil
